ce:section.ce:para:
The performance of organic solar cells based on a P3HT:PCBM blend was also investigated by a ZnPc-SWCNT covalent and noncovalent hybrid materials. The morphological features of the hybrids were determined using the scanning electron microscopy (SEM) technique and they were clear that the ZnPc film had a smooth film surface with small crystalline features. Moreover, SWCNTs functionalized with ZnPc led to different surface topographies related to the type of bonding (Fig. 23.18
                     ). The solar cell devices based on covalently bonded P3HT:PCBM-ZnPc-SWCNTs showed clear advancement in device performance with a power conversion efficiency of 5.3%. Solar cell devices prepared with P3HT:PCBM:ZnPc hybrids significantly improved the power conversion efficiency by 36% in comparison with the reference P3HT:PCBM-based device [53]. The same hybrid materials were tried for the electrical sensor response toward low concentrations of ammonia (10–50ppm). SWCNT-based materials functionalized both by covalent and noncovalent interactions with ZnPc led to an increase in the sensor response toward NH3 
                     [54].
